Quote: <i>ibid.</i> 210 ... the great Mountain Daisies [fn Celmisias of various species, notably <i>Cel. coriacea</i>.] and other plants which fleck the upland meadows with purest whites and softest yellows ... [<i>Celmisia coriacea</i>] The great white buttercup of the Southern Alps, handsomest of its genus, grows in profusion, only rivalled in beauty by the marguerite-like flowers of the numerous different kinds of `cotton plant' or mountain daisy [fn Species of <i>Celmisia</i>.]. To this assemblage of plants also belong the New Zealand `Edelweiss' [fn <i>Helichrysum grandiceps</i>.] (no mean representative of the Swiss plant [190] from which it derives its name), and the exquisite white-flowered ourisias  [fn <i>Ourisia macrocarpa</i> and <i>macrophylla</i>.], ...
